One final recommendation: keep a single document called the Wild Hawg Decision Log. Every meaningful choice—formula changes, packaging direction, supplier selection, pricing, branding—gets recorded with why you made the decision, the alternatives you considered, and the evidence behind it. Months later, when you’re scaling or troubleshooting, you’ll be able to retrace your reasoning instead of guessing why something was done. That kind of institutional memory is one of the simplest ways to build a stronger company from the beginning.